@flexiarg futon-theory/retrospective-stability
@title Retrospective Stability
@sigils [🌅/久]
@keywords stable, relabel, rewrite, future, proof, robust, invariant
@audience futon developers, pattern theorists
@tone analytic-foundational
@factor Keen investigation (dhammavicaya)
@references [futon-theory/symbolic-geodesic futon-theory/proof-path futon-theory/counter-ratchet]
@definition "A proof path P is retrospectively stable if: 1. For any future pattern F, P remains valid (may be relabeled with F) 2. For any stronger invariant I', P still satisfies I' 3. For any new evidence E, P is consistent with E Stability means: the structure holds, only the labels may change."
@references-extra ["Unstable paths require refactoring when the system evolves." "Stable paths require only annotation/relabeling." "The cost of instability is paid later, with interest."]

! conclusion: 
  A proof path is retrospectively stable if, after introducing any subsequent
  pattern, invariant, or evidence, it doesn't need to be rewritten - only
  relabeled. Stable proofs survive future refinement.

  + context: Systems evolve. New patterns get added, invariants get stronger,
    better evidence becomes available. Retrospective stability asks: will the
    work we do today survive tomorrow's improvements?

  + HOWEVER: The structural tension above manifests in the following concrete shapes (see substructure).
    + INDICATORS-OF-INSTABILITY:
      - Hardcoded assumptions that may not hold
      - Implicit invariants not formally stated
      - Edge cases handled by special logic
      - Paths that rely on current system limitations

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.
    + DESIGNING-FOR-STABILITY:
      - Make all invariants explicit and testable
      - Use patterns that generalize beyond current needs
      - Document assumptions that might change
      - Prefer simple paths over clever optimizations

    + STABILITY-LEVELS:
      - Unstable: New pattern/invariant invalidates the proof, must rewrite
      - Semi-stable: Proof valid but now inefficient, geodesic changed
      - Stable: Proof remains valid and geodesic, may get new labels

  + BECAUSE:
    Engineering time is finite. Work that must be redone is wasted work.
    Retrospective stability is an investment: pay slightly more now for
    paths that remain valid as the system grows.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Add stability analysis to pattern selection criteria]
    next[Track stability violations in PAR records]
